article.description:
Carmelo Anthony scored 23 points and Earl Boykins
hit a 3-pointer with 17 seconds left to lift the Denver Nuggets
past the Miami Heat, 101-99 on Saturday night.
article.headline: 'Melo scores 23 as Nuggets edge Heat at home
article.story:
DENVER (AP) -- Miami's zone got equal parts credit and blame for the Heat's 101-99 loss to the Denver Nuggets on Saturday night. With Dwyane Wade on the bench in foul trouble, the Nuggets took a 14-point lead on the opening basket of the fourth quarter but the Heat's stifling zone fueled a comeback, and Antoine Walker's field goal with 29 seconds put Miami ahead 99-98. Instead of switching strategies and going back to a matchup, the Heat stuck with what got them there -- and paid the price when Earl Boykins took a sweet pass from Andre Miller and sank an open 3-pointer with 17 seconds left that proved to be the winner. "Our guys did a great job of battling back from 14 down and quite simply, I blew it. That was a ridiculous call," Heat coach Stan Van Gundy said. "I mean, the zone got us back into the game. There's no reason we should have been in it on that last possession. The game is fully my responsibility. "I'm about ready to hang myself in there. That was an absolutely ridiculous coaching decision." Van Gundy was kicking himself for not calling off the zone and allowing Alonzo Mourning to do his thing in the paint. "It was just stupid. Especially when they brought Boykins back in the game. It was just stupid. We should have matched up and played our defense. Anything going to the glass, Zo would have had. It was an absolute stupid decision," Van Gundy said. "I don't even know what I was thinking. I wasn't in my right mind." The Heat had enough time to make up for tactical blunder but Greg Buckner, who replaced Boykins during the timeout, denied Wade the ball and James Posey ended up misfiring a 3-pointer. Carmelo Anthony led Denver with 23 points and Miller added 22. Wade led Miami with 32 points and Walker had 20. After the Nuggets built their lead to double digits, the zone was absolutely the right defense to make a game of it, Denver coach George Karl said. "Both teams were tired and Miami went to the zone and we didn't have enough energy to focus in on changing our style," said Karl, who was back on the sideline after serving a two-game suspension for criticizing the officiating Monday night. "And I thought it was a good move. Fortunately, Earl bailed us out with a great 3." It was another Boykins' 3-pointer that put Denver ahead 87-73 to start the fourth quarter. With Wade watching from the bench in foul trouble, Gary Payton, Walker and Posey hit 3-pointers in a 13-0 run that was fueled by the Heat's zone defense. "They played a good zone," Miller said. "They're known for doing that down the stretch. They kind of forced us into taking some bad shots and they hit some threes. Luckily." Miller said the Nuggets were surprised to see a zone in the closing seconds, however. The plan "was to attack and look for an open shot, or find somebody else," Miller said. "I saw Earl on the other side waving, so I kicked it to him and he knocked it down." Mourning didn't know what to think of the zone. "If we won the game, the zone would have been the best decision ever made. We didn't," Mourning said. "I don't think we need to break it down. It worked for us. Got us back in the damn game. If it's going to get us back in the game, then stick with it. "The problems was when the point guard drove, I had him behind the basket. Everybody came to the lane and I don't think we needed everybody coming to the lane like we did. All five guys in the paint. That left Boykins wide open," Mourning said. "If Boykins missed the shot, we would have been praising the zone." Mourning added: "I'm not a big zone guy. I want to guard people straight up." Anthony scored his 23 points despite foul trouble himself. While he made the most of his 28 minutes, his aggression left both him and a young fan red-faced. A preteen girl who was sitting in the front row behind the south basket was smacked in the head when Anthony flung the ball out of frustration after he was whistled for charging into Wade, negating a basket with about 3 minutes left in the first half. The girl wasn't injured and Anthony briefly chatted with her as the Nuggets filed past her on their way to the locker room with a 56-50 lead.

Game notes
Miami star Shaquille O'Neal, who has missed all but two games this season as he recovers from a sprained ankle, said he's going to try to practice Tuesday. ... Nuggets F Voshon Lenard returned after serving a one-game suspension for refusing assistant coach Scott Brooks' order to enter the game in the closing seconds Wednesday night against New Orleans. Lenard did not play Saturday night.
